# --- _include / _revinclude Performance ---

+8s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="We have about twenty minutes left. I want to touch on one more related topic before we wrap up — the _include and _revinclude performance issue. This came up in the context of CapabilityStatement because several implementers want to be able to declare limits on includes in their capability assertions."

+6s     say speaker="James Agnew" text="This is a real pain point for us. We have clients that do things like Patient?_revinclude=*. That's a query that says: give me all Patients and every resource that references those Patients. On a large server, that can be millions of resources. We have to set hard limits, but there's no standard way to communicate those limits."

+4s     say speaker="Cooper Thompson" text="We have the same problem at Epic. We cap _revinclude results at a hundred per parameter, but clients don't know that until they get back fewer results than they expected. There's no way to discover the limit in advance."

+5s     say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="This is exactly the kind of thing that the Feature Framework could handle. You'd have feature codes like 'supports _include' and 'max _include depth is 2' and 'max _revinclude results per parameter is 100'. These aren't things that fit naturally in CapabilityStatement's structure but they're very natural as feature assertions."

+4s     say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Or we could just add a few elements to CapabilityStatement. I know, I know — that makes it bigger. But we're talking about three or four simple integer limits. Is the Feature Framework really necessary for this or are we using a sledgehammer?"
+3s     chat id=chat-14 from="Gino Canessa" to="Everyone" text="Eric has a point — but the counter-argument is that every 'just add a few elements' over 10 years is why CapabilityStatement is 3MB now"

+5s     say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Hah, touché Gino. I walked right into that one."

+4s     say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="I think the answer is both. For R6, we add the critical limits to CapabilityStatement because that's where people look today. And the Feature Framework provides the extensible, long-term mechanism for everything else. We don't have to pick one."

+5s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Josh, I think that's pragmatic. Grahame, thoughts?"
+3s     say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="I'd prefer to not add more to CapabilityStatement, but I recognize the practical reality. Fine. A few integer limits for R6, with a note that this will migrate to the Feature Framework in R7."

+4s     say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="Can we get specific about what limits? I'd suggest: max include depth, max revinclude results per parameter, and a boolean for whether wildcard includes are supported."
+3s     say speaker="James Agnew" text="Add max total included resources per search response. That's the one our clients ask about most."
+2s     say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="OK, four items then."
+3s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Can someone open a tracker item for this? We need it before content freeze."
+2s     say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="I'll submit it today."
+1s     chat id=chat-15 from="Rick Geimer" to="Everyone" text="ACTION: Brian Postlethwaite to submit tracker for _include/_revinclude limits in CapabilityStatement"

# --- Wrap-up ---

+8s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="All right, we're at five minutes to the hour. Let me summarize. First, FHIR-34735 applied as editorial. Second, FHIR-32752 approved as persuasive — SubscriptionTopic canFilterBy moves to canonical. Third, FHIR-46167 approved persuasive with modification — combined search defaults to SHOULD. Fourth, we had a productive discussion on the Feature Framework. The IG is progressing. Grahame will continue working on the granularity question and bring a proposal to the next WGM."

+5s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Fifth, for the _include limits, Brian is opening a tracker item. And generally, we're all aware that R6 content freeze is November first so let's get our ducks in a row."
+2s     chat id=chat-16 from="Eric Haas" to="Everyone" text="Are those the same ducks that starved from document mode? 🦆"
+2s     chat id=chat-17 from="Grahame Grieve" to="Everyone" text="Those ducks are now features, Eric"

+3s     say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="One more thing — I want to encourage everyone to review the Feature Framework IG before the next call. It's at build.fhir.org/ig/HL7/capstmt. Comments are welcome on the Zulip stream or as tracker items."

+4s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Thanks Grahame. Any other business?"
+3s     say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Just a plug — if anyone's interested in the subscription side of this, we're doing a deep dive at the next connectathon. Track sign-up is open."
+2s     say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Great. Thanks everyone. Same time next week."

